Plotting Roman Roads

by jaro

11 August 2021

Roman roads network

This post concerns representation of ancient Roman roads with data from = the article:

Fousek J, Ka=C5=A1e V, Mertel A, V=C3=BDtvarov=C3=A1 E, Chalupa A (2018)= Spatial constraints on the diffusion of religious innovations: The case of= early Christianity in the Roman Empire. PLoS ONE 13(12): e0208744. https://doi= .org/10.1371/journal.pone.0208744

Preliminaries

Load "multigraph" package and check its version. 
# load package and check version
library=
("multigraph")
package=
Version("multigraph")
[1] '0.95'

Dataset

The dataset consists on three files of the Roman Empire transport networ= k between ancient cities:

  • s007 edgelist with cities travel costs
  • s006 city or settlement labels and their coordinates
  • s008 city or population estimates (among others)

Edgelist

Retrieve file s007.txt from GH repo with the =E2=80=9CEdge = list of the travel network=E2=80=9D (https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.= 0208744.s007).

# Edge list of the travel network
s007 <- read.csv("https://r=
aw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/s007.txt")

Look at some entries:

head(s007)
   from    to      cost
1 50176 50250 1.1616039
2 50176 50183 1.5454368
3 50176 50031 3.6945114
4 50177 50173 0.9312658
5 50177 50109 0.9578813
6 50178 50304 0.8077696

Object s007 then is a data frame with three columns; the tw= o first columns record edges from and to ancient Roman cities coded with an= ID. The third column has a weight of the travel cost (from-to..?) accordin= g to the ORBIS model where the minimum weight is:

min(s007[,,3])
[1] 0.07349514

Use function read.srt() from package "multiplex" to convert the edge list in s007 data frame into a matrix r= epresenting the network. In this case, the weights are the cells of the mat= rix.

# 's007' is a comma-separated table
net <- multiplex::read.srt<=
/span>(s007, header=3DTRUE, sep=3D",")

We look at the number of nodes in the network

dim(net)
[1] 648 648

and also at some of the entries in the net matrix for entit= y 50019.

net[<=
span class=3D"dv">18,1:=
6]
    50001     50002     50003     50004     50005     50006=20
0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.7754201

Graph representation

Since some travel cost weights are below 1, we need to make sure these e= ntries also appear in the graph by scaling the matrix.

# force directed layout 
multig=
raph(net*100, directed=3DFALSE, layout=3D"force", seed=3D1, pos=
=3D0)

Graph with Roman roads

City names

The network labels or the ancient Roman cities names are a file with coo= rdinates (https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0208744.s006)

# List of nodes of the travel network.
s006 <- read.csv("https://=
raw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/s006.txt")<=
/code>

Look at some entries:

head(s006)
  objectid           label XCOORD YCOORD
1    50002   Ad fl. Tigrim 37.325 42.196
2    50209 Iulia Concordia 45.757 12.844
3    50327            Roma 41.892 12.486
4    50319      Praetorium   31.5   15.5
5    50294        Patavium  45.41 11.877
6    50322         Puteoli 40.824 14.122

Object lbs is a vector with city names found in s006<= /code> according to net, which is lexicographically ordered. 

# second column in 's006' has the names
lbs <- as.vector(s006[matc=
h(as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]]), s006$=
objectid), 2])
# force directed layout with customized labels
multig=
raph(net*100, directed=3DFALSE, layout=3D"force", seed=3D1, pos=
=3D0, lbs=3Dlbs)=

Graph with Roman cities and roads 

# force directed layout with customized labels
scp <- list(pos=3D<=
span class=3D"dv">0, ecol=3D8, col=3D8,=
 fsize=3D5)
multig=
raph(net*100, directed=3DFALSE, layout=3D"force", seed=3D1, scope=
=3Dscp, lbs=3Dlbs, fcol=
=3D"#660066")

Graph with Roman cities and roads (customized)

A valued multigraph will represent the transportation costs ass= ociated to travel.

Cities with Populations

Cities from ORBIS with associated population estimates are in another fi= le (https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0208744.s008)

# ancient Roman cities with population estimates
s008 <- read.csv("https://=
raw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/s008.txt")<=
/code>

Look at some entries:

head(s008)
  objectid    label XCOORD YCOORD                  PLPATH rank p=
opest
1    50327     Roma 41.892 12.486     /places/423025/roma  100  1e+06
2    50294 Patavium  45.41 11.877 /places/393473/patavium   90  3e+04
3    50330 Rutupiae 51.294  1.332  /places/79664/rutupiae   70  7e+03
4    50008   Aelana 29.664 34.974   /places/746700/aelana   80  1e+04
5    50326   Regium 38.109 15.644  /places/452416/rhegion   80  8e+03
6    50329 Rusicade 36.883  6.906 /places/305137/rusicade   80  1e+04

where the last column has some city=E2=80=99s population.

However not all cities are covered in file s008.

head(match(as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]]), s008$objectid), 20)
 [1]  NA  NA  NA  NA  NA  NA  NA   4  NA  37  91  24  NA  86  NA=
  NA  83  90  87 236
# second column has city names
lbs0 <- as.vector(s008[mat=
ch(as.numeric(dimnames<=
/span>(net)[[1]]), s008$objectid),2])
# force directed layout with customized node labels
multig=
raph(net*100, directed=3DFALSE, layout=3D"force", seed=3D1, scope=
=3Dscp, lbs=3Dlbs0)

Graph with large Roman cities and road network

In principle, the population size can be reflected in the graph of the n= etwork

# seventh column has population estimates
popl <- as.vector(s008[mat=
ch(as.numeric(dimnames<=
/span>(net)[[1]]), s008$objectid),7])
# force directed layout with customized node size and labels<=
/span>
multig=
raph(net*100, directed=3DFALSE, layout=3D"force", seed=3D1, scope=
=3Dscp, lbs=3Dlbs0, cex=
=3Dpopl)

Graph with large Roman cities and road network (customized)

Coordinates

Certainly, other layout options for the graph may apply as well includin= g using the coordinates of the settlements. We use the coordinates found in= s006 to make the new plot

# coordinates are the third and fourth columns
cds <- as.vector(s006[matc=
h(as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]]), s006$=
objectid), 3:4])

However, there are three duplicate labels in s006.

# city names are in the ssecond column
rownam=
es(cds) <- as.vector=
(s006[match(as.numeric<=
/span>(dimnames(net)[[1=
]]), s006$objectid), 2]=
)
#Error in `.rowNamesDF<-`(x, value =3D value) :=20
#  duplicate 'row.names' are not allowed
#In addition: Warning message:
#non-unique values when setting 'row.names': =E2=80=98Isca=E2=80=99, =E2=80=
=98Noviomagus=E2=80=99, =E2=80=98Venta=E2=80=99
